WEST NILE VIRUS - ITALY (03): (LOMBARDY) FURTHER CLARIFICATION
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon 24 May 2010
From: Giuseppe Ippolito <giuseppe.ippolito@inmi.it> [edited]


Evidence of WNV circulation in Italy has been found since 2008 in
animals [1,2], humans [3], and mosquitoes. Up until now, the spread
has been demonstrated in 3 regions of the northeast (Emilia-Romagna,
Veneto and Lombardy). A recent communication posted on ProMED
(archive number 20100520.1670) reports a newspaper article in which
78 human cases are erroneously reported in 2009, with 3 deaths. In
fact, 78 are the *suspected* human cases with neuro-invasive disease
detected from June to October 2009 through the surveillance system in
place in Emilia-Romagna; among them, 9 were confirmed cases of WNV,
with 3 deaths [4]. In total, 16 human cases were reported in Italy in
2009, all from the 3 regions already cited [5]. Up to now, no data
are available about the occurrence of human cases in 2010, but these
cases are expected, as mosquito activity will grow during the
spring-summer period.

Since last year [2009], active and passive surveillance strategies
are in place for the monitoring of WNV in humans, equines, birds and
mosquitoes [4] in Emilia-Romagna and Veneto. Surveillance has
recently started also in 68 municipalities in Lombardy, the newspaper
article translated and posted on ProMED (archive number
20100520.1670) says. Similar initiatives are not widely in place in
other Italian regions, such that the real estimation of the disease
[and virus] diffusion in Italy is difficult.

The virus "exploding" cited in the ProMED post is a misleading
translation. In Italian, especially in journalistic writing, the term
"explosion" is used in the sense of an "appearance and diffusion" of
a phenomenon and does not necessarily refer to a dramatic increase of
something.

References cited:
1. Calistri P, Giovannini A, Savini G, Monaco F, Bonfanti L, Ceolin
C, et al. West Nile virus transmission in 2008 in North-Eastern
Italy. Zoonosis and Public Health. 2010;57(3):211-9.
doi:10.1111/j.1863-2378.2009.01303.x.

2. Emilia-Romagna West Nile regional surveillance plan. 2009.
Available from:
<http://www.saluter.it/wcm/saluter/sanitaer/ssr/assistenza_territoriale/Dipartimento_sanita_pubblica/documentazione/lk_prevenzione/page/lk_piani/piani/lk
/WND_2009.pdf> (Italian version).

3. Rossini G, Cavrini F, Pierro A, Macini P, Finarelli AC, Po C, et
al. First human case of West Nile virus neuroinvasive infection in
Italy, September 2008 case report. EuroSurveill. 2008;13(41).
pii=19002. Available from:
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=19002>.

4. Angelini P, Tamba M, Finarelli AC, Bellini R, Albieri A, Bonilauri
P, Cavrini F, Dottori M, Gaibani P, Martini E, Mattivi A, Pierro AM,
Rugna G, Sambri V, Squintani G, Macini P. West Nile virus circulation
in Emilia-Romagna, Italy: the integrated surveillance system 2009.
Euro Surveill. 2010;15(16):pii=19547. Available online:
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=19547>.

5. Rizzo C, Vescio F, Declich S, Finarelli AC, Macini P, Mattivi A,
Rossini G, Piovesan C, Barzon L, Palu G, Gobbi F, Macchi L, Pavan A,
Magurano F, Ciufolini MG, Nicoletti L, Salmaso S, Rezza G. West Nile
virus transmission with human cases in Italy, August - September
2009. Euro Surveill. 2009;14(40):pii=19353. Available online:
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=19353>.

